(203, 1, '2017-06-04 13:27:26', '2017-06-04 13:27:26', 'Who is on the other side of the split? In Cosmetic Ideas, Inc. v. IAC/Interactive, the Ninth Circuit came to the opposite conclusion and adopted the “application” approach. According to the Ninth Circuit, the statute’s definition of “registration” is ambiguous because some sections (e.g., Section 408) indicate that there are no prerequisites to registration other than a completed application. Moreover, the Ninth Circuit felt that the application approach is more efficient: even if the application is rejected, the plaintiff is going to get to sue anyway, so why wait around just to engage in the kind of “needless formality” that the 1976 Copyright Act was supposed to eliminate?', 'Who is on the other side of the split?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'lorem-ipsum-is-simply-dummy-text-of-the-printing-and-typesetting-industry-3', '', '', '2017-06-08 10:58:05', '2017-06-08 10:58:05', '', 0, 'http://35.154.128.159:83/?p=203', 0, 'post', '', 0),
